The key insight in this problem is recognizing that the shortest path for each boy forms a quadrilateral that can be divided into two 30-60-90 triangles. By using the properties of these special triangles, we can calculate the distance traveled by each boy and then multiply it by the total number of boys to find the total distance traveled.
The thicker solid line in the diagram shows the shortest path that one person could travel.

\begin{center}
\begin{asy}
import olympiad; import geometry; size(100); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8)); dotfactor=4;
draw(unitcircle);
for(int i = 0; i <= 6; ++i){
dot(dir(60*i + 30));
}
draw(dir(30)--dir(90)--dir(150)--dir(270)--cycle);
draw(dir(90)--dir(270),dotted);
\end{asy}
\end{center}

The circle is equally divided into six 60-degree arcs, so the short distance (from one boy to an adjacent boy) is 40 feet, the same as the radius.

The dotted line is a diameter that separates the quadrilateral into two 30-60-90 triangles. In a 30-60-90 triangle, the longer leg is $\sqrt{3}$ times the shorter leg. So, the longer leg of each triangle is:

$\frac{80\sqrt{3}}{2} = 40\sqrt{3} \text{ feet}$

Each person travels:

$40\sqrt{3} + 40 + 40 + 40\sqrt{3} = 80 + 80\sqrt{3} \text{ feet}$

After all six people did this, the total distance traveled is:

$6(80 + 80\sqrt{3}) = 480 + 480\sqrt{3} \text{ feet}$

The least total distance traveled is $480 + 480\sqrt{3}$ feet.

The key insight is to recognize that a rotation matrix in 2D has the form:
$\begin{pmatrix} 
\cos \theta & -\sin \theta \\
\sin \theta & \cos \theta
\end{pmatrix}$

Where $\theta$ is the angle of rotation. By setting up an equation with the given input and output vectors, we can solve for $\cos \theta$ and $\sin \theta$. Once we have these values, we can apply the rotation matrix to the vector $\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ to get the final rotated vector.
1) The rotation matrix must be of the form:
   $\begin{pmatrix}
   \cos \theta & -\sin \theta \\
   \sin \theta & \cos \theta
   \end{pmatrix}$

2) Set up the equation:
   $\begin{pmatrix}
   \cos \theta & -\sin \theta \\
   \sin \theta & \cos \theta
   \end{pmatrix}
   \begin{pmatrix}
   13 \\ 0
   \end{pmatrix} =
   \begin{pmatrix}
   5 \\ -12
   \end{pmatrix}$

3) This gives us:
   $\cos \theta = \frac{5}{13}$ and $\sin \theta = -\frac{12}{13}$

4) Apply the rotation matrix with the solved values to the vector $\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$:
   $\begin{pmatrix}
   \frac{5}{13} & \frac{12}{13} \\
   -\frac{12}{13} & \frac{5}{13}
   \end{pmatrix}
   \begin{pmatrix}
   0 \\ 1
   \end{pmatrix} =
   \begin{pmatrix}
   12/13 \\ 5/13
   \end{pmatrix}$
Therefore, the rotation takes the vector $\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ to $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 12/13 \\ 5/13 \end{pmatrix}}$.

The key insight here is to recognize that by connecting midpoints of opposite sides and opposite vertices in a regular octagon, we divide the octagon into congruent triangular regions. This allows us to compare the areas of different polygons within the octagon by simply counting the number of these congruent regions they contain.
We connect the midpoints of all opposite sides and we connect all opposite vertices: {{DGM:86264ed238cb5cf4}}

Because of symmetry, these lines split the octagon into 16 congruent regions.  Quadrilateral $ABMO$ is made up of three of these regions and pentagon $EDCMO$ is made up of five of these regions.  Hence, $[ABMO]/[EDCMO] = \boxed{\frac{3}{5}}$.

The key insight in this solution is to recognize that the numerator and denominator can be simplified by combining the fractions within each term. By doing so, we can express the numerator and denominator as a ratio of factorials, which can then be simplified to obtain the final answer.
1. Combine the fractions within each term in the numerator and denominator:
   $$\begin{align*}
   \frac{(1 + 17) \left( 1 + \dfrac{17}{2} \right) \left( 1 + \dfrac{17}{3} \right) \dotsm \left( 1 + \dfrac{17}{19} \right)}{(1 + 19) \left( 1 + \dfrac{19}{2} \right) \left( 1 + \dfrac{19}{3} \right) \dotsm \left( 1 + \dfrac{19}{17} \right)} &= \frac{\dfrac{18}{1} \cdot \dfrac{19}{2} \cdot \dfrac{20}{3} \dotsm \dfrac{36}{19}}{\dfrac{20}{1} \cdot \dfrac{21}{2} \cdot \dfrac{22}{3} \dotsm \dfrac{36}{17}}
   \end{align*}$$

2. Express the numerator and denominator as a ratio of factorials:
   $$\begin{align*}
   \frac{\dfrac{18}{1} \cdot \dfrac{19}{2} \cdot \dfrac{20}{3} \dotsm \dfrac{36}{19}}{\dfrac{20}{1} \cdot \dfrac{21}{2} \cdot \dfrac{22}{3} \dotsm \dfrac{36}{17}} &= \frac{\dfrac{36!/17!}{19!}}{\dfrac{36!/19!}{17!}}
   \end{align*}$$

3. Simplify the ratio of factorials to obtain the final answer:
   $$\begin{align*}
   \frac{\dfrac{36!/17!}{19!}}{\dfrac{36!/19!}{17!}} &= \boxed{1}
   \end{align*}$$
The value of the given expression is \boxed{1}.

The key insight in this problem is to simplify both congruence relationships and observe that $2x$ cannot be equivalent to both 2 and 4 modulo 12 simultaneously. This leads to the conclusion that there are no solutions for $x$ that satisfy both congruence relationships within the given range.
Step 1: Simplify the first congruence relationship.
$$\begin{align*}
x - 1 \equiv 1 - x \pmod{12} &\implies 2x \equiv 2 \pmod{12}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Simplify the second congruence relationship.
$$\begin{align*}
x - 2 \equiv 2 - x \pmod{12} &\implies 2x \equiv 4 \pmod{12}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Observe that $2x$ cannot be equivalent to both 2 and 4 modulo 12 simultaneously.

Step 4: Conclude that there are no solutions for $x$ that satisfy both congruence relationships within the given range.
